particulars: First successful westbound (Manila-to-Acapulco) Pacific crossing. Piloted by Andres de Urdaneta, an Augustinian friar who discovered the tornaviaje (return route) via the Kuroshio Current and westerlies. Departed from Cebu as part of the Legazpi expedition. Urdaneta sailed north to approximately 38 degrees N latitude before turning east, arriving at Acapulco after about 4 months.
Small patache that separated from the Legazpi fleet and independently found a return route to New Spain, arriving before the San Pablo. Often overlooked in favor of Urdaneta's voyage.
One of the first eastbound supply galleons sent to reinforce the Legazpi settlement in the Philippines.
Early westbound crossing carrying initial Philippine trade goods. Manila had just been established as the colonial capital.
Reinforcement galleon sent during the early period of the trade. Carried silver to purchase Chinese goods arriving in Manila.

cargo_description: silk, porcelain, gold, musk, and beeswax
particulars: Captured off Cabo San Lucas by the English privateer Thomas Cavendish on 4 November 1587 during his circumnavigation. The 700-ton galleon carried an immensely valuable cargo. The crew and passengers were set ashore and the ship was burned. One of the most famous galleon captures.

Storm-damaged and driven ashore at Urado, Tosa Province, Japan, in October 1596. The cargo was seized by order of Toyotomi Hideyoshi. A boastful pilot allegedly showed Hideyoshi a map of Spanish conquests, contributing to the Shogun's suspicion of Christians. The incident precipitated the martyrdom of the Twenty-Six Martyrs of Japan in February 1597 at Nagasaki.
Eastbound crossing of the San Felipe before its ill-fated westbound return voyage later that year.

Sunk on 14 December 1600 in battle against the Dutch ship Mauritius commanded by Olivier van Noort off Fortune Island (Nasugbu, Batangas). Acting Governor Antonio de Morga had hastily converted the merchant galleon into a warship. Over 350 lives were lost. The wreck was discovered in 1991 by Franck Goddio and yielded over 34,000 artifacts, now in museums worldwide.
Routine westbound crossing during the early consolidation of the Manila Galleon trade.
Eastbound supply galleon carrying silver for the China trade.
Westbound crossing during a period of rapid expansion in the transpacific silk trade.
Standard eastbound voyage carrying silver for the purchase of Chinese silk and other Asian goods.

Wrecked on the coast of Japan near Onjuku, Chiba Province, on 30 September 1609. The former interim Governor of the Philippines Don Rodrigo de Vivero was aboard. He was received by Tokugawa Ieyasu and eventually returned to New Spain via a Japanese-built ship, the San Buenaventura, opening early diplomatic contacts.
Successful westbound crossing during the peak years of the silk trade.
Eastbound crossing carrying substantial silver shipment. The Spanish peso was the principal currency of the China trade.
Departed Cavite and was never seen again. Presumed lost with all hands in a typhoon in the Philippine Sea. One of several galleons that simply vanished on the long Pacific crossing.
Large galleon carrying one of the most valuable cargoes of the decade. Arrived in Acapulco after a 5-month crossing.

cargo_description: silver bullion, church vestments, and wine
particulars: Standard eastbound voyage. Spanish authorities periodically attempted to limit the value of cargo to protect Seville merchants.

cargo_description: silk, gold, porcelain, and precious stones
particulars: Wrecked on the reef at Agingan Point, Saipan, Mariana Islands, in September 1638 during a typhoon. Approximately 180 of the 400 people aboard perished. The survivors reached Guam. The wreck was discovered by treasure hunter William Mathers in 1987. One of the most famous Manila Galleon wrecks.
Eastbound galleon during the mid-century. Portugal's separation from Spain (1640) disrupted some Asian trade networks.
Crossed during a period when the Dutch were aggressively blockading Manila Bay, though this ship eluded the blockade.
Carried reinforcements and silver during the Dutch-Spanish conflicts in the Philippines.
Wrecked in a typhoon near the San Bernardino Strait shortly after departure. The ship broke apart on a reef. A portion of the crew and passengers were rescued.

cargo_description: silver bullion, mercury, and ecclesiastical goods
particulars: Eastbound crossing during the mid-century slump in trade caused by European wars and colonial administration issues.
Successful westbound crossing during a relatively stable period for the galleon trade.
Left Cavite and was never heard from again. Believed lost in a typhoon somewhere in the Philippine Sea. No wreckage or survivors were ever found.

cargo_description: silk bales, cotton cloth, and beeswax
particulars: Relatively small galleon that made a slow but successful crossing.
Major silver shipment to Manila. By mid-century, the Philippines had become a critical funnel for New World silver into the Chinese economy.
Westbound crossing during the Koxinga crisis. Zheng Chenggong (Koxinga) threatened Manila in 1662, disrupting the China trade.
Eastbound voyage during the period when the Koxinga threat caused a temporary collapse in Chinese trade at Manila.
Successful crossing during the early years of the Spanish Regency under Queen Mariana of Austria.
Vanished on the Pacific crossing. No trace of the ship or its crew was ever found. Presumed lost in a storm.

cargo_description: silk bales, chinaware, and gold thread
particulars: Large galleon carrying a highly valuable cargo during a prosperous period of the Manila trade.
Eastbound galleon carrying silver and New World products to Manila.
Wrecked in a typhoon near the Catanduanes Island east of Luzon shortly after entering the open Pacific. Most of the crew survived by reaching shore.
Long but successful crossing. By the 1680s, Manila's Parian (Chinese quarter) housed thousands of Chinese merchants.
One of the largest galleons of the era. Named after the revered crucifix of Burgos in Spain.

cargo_description: silk, gold, porcelain, and precious stones
particulars: Encountered the English privateer squadron and was sunk on 25 June 1694 in a battle off Lubang Island, south of Manila. The battle lasted several hours. The San Jose went down with an immensely valuable cargo. Hundreds of lives were lost.

Departed Cavite in July 1693 and was never seen again. One of the most mysterious losses in galleon history. Carried approximately 400 people. Various theories include typhoon, structural failure, or foundering in the open Pacific.
Turn-of-century crossing. The War of the Spanish Succession (1701-1714) would soon threaten the galleon route.
Eastbound voyage during the War of the Spanish Succession. The galleon trade continued despite the European conflict.
Caught in a severe typhoon near the Embocadero (San Bernardino Strait) and driven onto rocks. Most of the crew perished.
Successful westbound crossing during the War of the Spanish Succession.
Post-war silver shipment. The Treaty of Utrecht (1713) ended the War of the Spanish Succession and brought renewed stability.
Routine westbound crossing in the post-war period. Trade volumes gradually recovered.

cargo_description: silk, porcelain, spices, and cotton textiles
particulars: Prosperous crossing in the early Bourbon era. The new Bourbon dynasty modernized some aspects of colonial trade.
Heavily damaged by a typhoon east of the Philippines. The ship limped back toward Luzon but broke apart on a reef near Catanduanes. Approximately half the crew survived.
Successful westbound crossing. The 1730s were a relatively stable period for the galleon trade.
Eastbound crossing of the Covadonga. This ship would later become famous for its capture by the English.

Captured on 20 June 1743 off Cape Espiritu Santo by Commodore George Anson's HMS Centurion during his circumnavigation. The prize contained 1,313,843 pieces of eight and 35,682 ounces of virgin silver. Anson's crew shared the enormous prize money. The capture was a sensation in Britain and humiliated Spain. Anson went on to become First Lord of the Admiralty.
Successful crossing during the War of the Austrian Succession. The threat of British privateers was ever-present.
Post-Anson-capture eastbound voyage. After the loss of the Covadonga, the Spanish improved galleon defenses and varied sailing dates.

cargo_description: silk, porcelain, cotton textiles, and spices
particulars: Large galleon with improved armament after the Anson raid. Carried 60 cannon and a crew augmented with soldiers.
The Santisima Trinidad was one of the largest galleons ever built, approximately 2,000 tons. Built in the shipyards of Bagatao, Sorsogon. She served on the galleon route for over a decade.
The enormous Santisima Trinidad on her westbound crossing. She was the pride of the galleon fleet.
Routine westbound crossing. Tea was becoming an increasingly valuable part of the cargo.
Eastbound crossing during the Seven Years' War. The Spanish tried to maintain neutrality until 1762.
One of several galleons built in Philippine shipyards using local hardwoods like molave and lanang.

Captured on 30 October 1762 by the British naval squadron under Admiral Samuel Cornish during the British occupation of Manila in the Seven Years' War. The Santisima Trinidad was the richest prize of the Manila campaign. She was carrying approximately 3 million pesos in cargo. The British held Manila from 1762 to 1764.
Arrived in Manila shortly before the British invasion. The silver she carried was seized by the British.
First galleon to depart after the British returned Manila to Spain in 1764. Trade was much reduced by the occupation's effects.
Post-occupation recovery voyage. The Bourbon Reforms were beginning to alter colonial trade structures.
Eastbound voyage during the Bourbon Reform era. The Jesuits had just been expelled from Spanish territories in 1767.
Mid-Bourbon era crossing. The Royal Company of the Philippines would soon be established to rationalize the Manila trade.
Struck by a severe typhoon east of the Philippines and badly damaged. The ship managed to turn back but was wrecked on the coast of Samar. Most of the crew survived by reaching shore in boats.
Late-period eastbound crossing. European manufactured goods were increasingly included alongside silver.
Arrived in Acapulco the same year as the American Revolution began. Spain's involvement in that war would further strain colonial resources.
Crossed during the period when Spain was preparing to enter the American Revolutionary War against Britain (1779).
Eastbound crossing during the American Revolutionary War. Spanish naval resources were stretched thin.
Governor Basco had founded the Economic Society of the Philippines and was promoting Philippine agricultural exports alongside Chinese goods.
The Royal Company of the Philippines (est. 1785) was about to be chartered, introducing direct trade between Spain and Manila and weakening the galleon trade monopoly.
Late-period crossing. The Royal Company of the Philippines was now operating, creating competition for the galleon traders.
Crossed during the last years of Charles III's reign. The galleon trade was increasingly seen as an anachronism by Bourbon reformers.
Eastbound crossing in the year of the French Revolution. The winds of change were blowing for all European empires.
The Nootka Crisis of 1790 between Spain and Britain highlighted Spain's declining naval power.
One of the last galleon crossings before the outbreak of war between Spain and Revolutionary France in 1793.
Wartime eastbound crossing. Silver shipments continued despite the European conflicts.
Sailed during the brief peace before Spain allied with France against Britain in 1796, making the Pacific crossing increasingly dangerous from British raiders.

One of the last galleons of the 18th century. The San Martin represents the twilight of the great Pacific trade. British naval supremacy after the Battle of Cape St Vincent (1797) made ocean crossings increasingly perilous for Spanish ships.
Damaged by a typhoon in the Philippine Sea. The ship's masts were carried away and she drifted helplessly before sinking. Some crew members were rescued after drifting in boats for weeks.
Turn-of-century eastbound crossing. Napoleon's rise was about to transform the Spanish Empire.
Early 19th-century crossing. The galleon trade was now a shadow of its former glory, reduced by the Royal Company, Bourbon reforms, and wartime disruptions.
Eastbound crossing during the brief Peace of Amiens (1802). A rare period of peace in the Napoleonic Wars.
The Magallanes was one of the last purpose-built galleons. Named after Ferdinand Magellan, whose expedition first crossed the Pacific in 1521.
Crossed in the year of Trafalgar. Spain's naval power was shattered, though the Pacific remained relatively safe from British incursion by this point.
Eastbound silver delivery. The amount of silver shipped was now far less than in the trade's peak years.
Arrived to find New Spain in turmoil. Napoleon had invaded Spain in 1808, triggering the Peninsular War and colonial independence movements.
Carried news of Napoleon's invasion of Spain. The Philippines remained loyal to the Spanish resistance government.
The Mexican War of Independence began on 16 September 1810, initiated by Father Miguel Hidalgo. This would ultimately end the galleon trade.
Crossed during the early stages of the Mexican independence war. Acapulco was contested territory, complicating the galleon's arrival.
One of the last eastbound crossings. Insurgent forces in Mexico made it increasingly difficult to send silver to Manila.
The Cortes of Cadiz in 1813 would formally abolish the galleon trade monopoly, though the Mexican insurgency had already made regular crossings impossible.
Penultimate galleon crossing. The Cortes of Cadiz formally abolished the Manila Galleon trade monopoly in 1813. The 250-year-old trade route was nearing its end.

The LAST Manila Galleon. The Magallanes departed Cavite in July 1815 and arrived in Acapulco in late 1815, ending 250 years of the transpacific galleon trade (1565-1815). The Mexican War of Independence and the abolition of the trade monopoly by the Cortes of Cadiz made continuation impossible. It was the longest-running maritime trade route in history.
Carried the navigator Sebastian Vizcaino, who had previously explored the California coast. He was sent as ambassador to Japan and continued to Edo to meet the Shogun Tokugawa Ieyasu.
On the westbound crossing, Captain Unamuno was instructed to explore the California coast. He made landfall at Morro Bay in October 1587 before continuing to Acapulco.
Routine late-16th-century crossing. The San Martin served on the galleon route for several years.

Caught in a typhoon south of Japan on the northern great-circle route. The masts were lost and the ship gradually took on water. She sank in the western Pacific. Only a few crew members survived by clinging to wreckage and being rescued by a passing vessel.
Wrecked on the Embocadero (San Bernardino Strait) after encountering a typhoon shortly after departure from Cavite. The ship was driven onto a reef. Most of the crew reached shore.
Annual galleon crossing. Early establishment of the transpacific trade route.
